1394  // Suppose we have n nested loops, loop_0 being the outermost one, and
1395  // loop_n being the OSR loop. We start iterating the bytecode at the header
1396  // of loop_n (the OSR loop), and then we peel the part of the the body of
1397  // loop_{n-1} following the end of loop_n. We then rewind the iterator to
1398  // the header of loop_{n-1}, and so on until we have partly peeled loop 0.
1399  // The full loop_0 body will be generating with the rest of the function,
1400  // outside the OSR generation.
1401 
1402  // To do so, if we are visiting a loop, we continue to visit what's left
1403  // of its parent, and then when reaching the parent's JumpLoop, we do not
1404  // create any jump for that but rewind the bytecode iterator to visit the
1405  // parent loop entirely, and so on.
1406

1408  bytecode_analysis().GetLoopInfoFor(osr_entry).parent_offset();
1409  while (current_parent_offset != -1) {
1410  const LoopInfo& current_parent_loop =
1411  bytecode_analysis().GetLoopInfoFor(current_parent_offset);
1412  // We iterate until the back edge of the parent loop, which we detect by
1413  // the offset that the JumpLoop targets.
1414  for (; !bytecode_iterator().done(); bytecode_iterator().Advance()) {
1415  if (bytecode_iterator().current_bytecode() ==
1416  interpreter::Bytecode::kJumpLoop &&
1417  bytecode_iterator().GetJumpTargetOffset() == current_parent_offset) {
1418  // Reached the end of the current parent loop.
1419  break;
1420  }
1421  VisitSingleBytecode();
1422  }
1423  DCHECK(!bytecode_iterator()
1424  .done()); // Should have found the loop's jump target.
1425

1427  // handlers here because the omitted JumpLoop bytecode can still be the
1428  // target of jumps or the first bytecode after a try block.
1429  ExitThenEnterExceptionHandlers(bytecode_iterator().current_offset());
1430  SwitchToMergeEnvironment(bytecode_iterator().current_offset());
1431 
1432  // This jump is the jump of our parent loop, which is not yet created.
1433  // So we do not build the jump nodes, but restore the bytecode and the
1434  // SourcePosition iterators to the values they had when we were visiting
1435  // the offset pointed at by the JumpLoop we've just reached.
1436  // We have already built nodes for inner loops, but now we will
1437  // iterate again over them and build new nodes corresponding to the same
1438  // bytecode offsets. Any jump or reference to this inner loops must now
1439  // point to the new nodes we will build, hence we clear the relevant part
1440  // of the environment.
1441  // Completely clearing the environment is not possible because merge
1442  // environments for forward jumps out of the loop need to be preserved
